21:30.060 --> 21:33.980
It leads him to complete and total skepticism.

21:35.260 --> 21:39.980
Because if there is no cause and effect, how can we predict the future?

21:41.100 --> 21:42.540
How can we generalize?

21:43.980 --> 21:47.820
How can we say that because things have happened a certain way in the past,

21:48.380 --> 21:50.700
therefore they will happen that way in the future?

21:51.340 --> 21:53.900
How can we ever formulate scientific laws?

21:53.900 --> 21:59.980
How can we even have science to all of which Hume's answer is, you can't.

22:00.380 --> 22:08.300
We have, he says, no reason on earth to assume that nature follows law.

22:09.420 --> 22:12.700
We have no reason to assume that nature is uniform.

22:12.700 --> 22:16.460
We have no reason to assume that the future will be like the past.

22:17.820 --> 22:20.860
This is known as the problem of induction.

22:21.580 --> 22:27.420
And the problem of induction is what makes you think that because something has happened

22:27.500 --> 22:32.220
a certain way repeatedly in the past, it will therefore happen that way in the future.

22:33.180 --> 22:39.660
Now, of course, if there are necessary connections in reality, if there are actual laws

22:39.660 --> 22:46.220
which nature must obey, then you can validly generalize from experience under the appropriate

22:46.220 --> 22:54.620
circumstances. But if you destroy causality and you reduce it, nature, to simply unintelligible,

22:54.700 --> 23:01.340
brute conjunction of events without any necessity, then anything is possible at the next instant.

23:02.060 --> 23:06.860
And the fact that something has happened a thousand times proves nothing about the future.

23:07.580 --> 23:10.540
It's simply been a run of coincidence.

23:12.140 --> 23:14.940
